org.jcvi.jillion.core.util.iter

Interface StreamingIterator<T>

  • All Superinterfaces:
    AutoCloseable, Closeable, Iterator<T>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    PeekableStreamingIterator<T>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractBlockingStreamingIterator, DataStoreIterator, DataStoreStreamingIterator, LargeFastaIdIterator, QualitySequenceFastaDataStoreIteratorImpl

    public interface StreamingIterator<T>
extends Closeable, Iterator<T>
    StreamingIterator is an Iterator that might not have its next element loaded into memory. StreamingIterators are useful when iterating over elements that are resource intensive so that only as few as the current element need to actually be loaded into memory at one time. StreamingIterators are often used to iterate over records stored in files. Client code must explicitly close() this iterator when done iterating (preferably in a try-finally block) so that any resources used by this iterator can be cleaned up. Not completely iterating over all the objects in this iterator and not calling close() could in some implementations cause memory leaks, deadlocks and/or permanently blocked background threads. Closing a StreamingIterator before it has finished iterating over all the records will cause hasNext() to return false and next() to throw a NoSuchElementException as if this iterator has finished iterating.

    NOTE: some implementations might throw unchecked exceptions in hasNext() or next() if there are problems fetching the next element to be iterated.

    Author:
    dkatzel

      • close

        void close()
        Close this iterator and clean up any open resources. This will force this iterator's hasNext() to return false and next() to throw a NoSuchElementException as if there were no more elements to iterate over.

        If this method is not explicitly called and this iterator still has elements left to iterate over, then some implementations could cause memory leaks, deadlocks and/or permanently blocked threads.

        default Stream<T> toStream()
        Convert this StreamingIterator into a Java 8 Stream. The returned Stream must be closed when finished so it is recommended that it is enclosed in a try-with-resource block. Note: The returned Stream will iterate over the elements in this Stream so if this method is called, do not call next() or close() directly or make any assumptions from the returned values of hasNext().
